Overview

This lab demonstrates how to create a managed data disk in Microsoft Azure and attach it to a Windows Virtual Machine. The attached disk can be used for additional storage such as application data, logs, or databases.

Objective

Create a managed data disk in Azure

Attach the disk to an existing Windows Virtual Machine

Initialize and format the disk inside the VM

Make the disk available for use

Prerequisites

An active Microsoft Azure subscription

Basic knowledge of Azure Portal

A running Windows Virtual MachMachine

Steps Performed
1. Create a Windows Virtual Machine

Go to the Azure Portal.

Navigate to Virtual Machines.

Click Create > Azure Virtual Machine.

Select:

Resource Group

VM Name

Region

Windows Server Image

Configure administrator username and password.

Review and create the VM.

2Create a Data Disk

In the Azure Portal, search for Disks.

Click Create Disk.

Provide the following details:

Resource Group

Disk Name

Region

Disk Size

Performance Type (Standard SSD / Premium SSD)

Click Review + Create and then Create.

3. Attach Data Disk to the VM

Go to Virtual Machines.

Select the created Windows VM.Click Disks under the Settings section.

Click Attach existing disk.

Select the newly created disk.

Click Save.

4. Initialize the Disk in Windows

Connect to the VM using Remote Desktop (RDP).

Open Disk Management.

The new disk will appear as Offline/Unallocated.

Initialize the disk (MBR or GPT).

Create a New Simple Volume.

Format the disk with NTFS and assign a drive letter.Verify the Disk

Open File Explorer.

Confirm the new drive appears and is ready for use.

Result

A managed data disk was successfully created, attached to a Windows Virtual Machine, and configured within the operating system for storage use.

